{{Infobox legislation |short_title = Representation of Natives Act, 1936 |legislature = |image = Coat of Arms of South Africa (1932-2000).svg |imagesize = |imagealt = |caption = |long_title = Act to make special provision for the representation of natives in Parliament and in the provincial council of the Province of the Cape of Good Hope and to that end to amend the law in force in that province relating to the registration of natives as voters for Parliament or a provincial council; to establish a Natives Representative Council for the Union; and to provide for other incidental matters. |citation = Act No. 12 of 1936 |territorial_extent = |enacted_by = [[Parliament of South Africa]] |date_enacted = |date_passed = |enacted_by2 = |date_enacted2 = |date_passed2 = |date_assented = |royal_assent = 20 April 1936 |date_signed = |date_commenced = 10 July 1936 |date_of_expiry = |date_repealed = 19 June 1959 |administered_by = [[Minister of Bantu Administration and Development, and Bantu Education|Minister of Native Affairs]] |bill = |bill_citation = |bill_date = |introduced_by = |1st_reading = |2nd_reading = |3rd_reading = |conf_committee_passed = |bill2 = |bill_citation2 = |bill_date2 = |introduced_by2 = |1st_reading2 = |2nd_reading2 = |3rd_reading2 = |conf_committee_passed2 = |date_conf_committee = |white_paper = |committee_report = |amendments = |repeals = [[Promotion of Bantu Self-government Act, 1959]] |related_legislation = [[Separate Representation of Voters Act, 1951]] |summary = |keywords = |status = repealed }} The '''Representation of Natives Act''' No 12 of 1936 (commenced 10 July) was legislation passed in South Africa which further reduced black rights at the time.<ref name="Loveland1999">{{cite book|author=Ian Loveland|title=By Due Process of Law: Racial Discrimination and the Right to Vote in South Africa 1855-1960|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=h7u_SUxHpzwC&dq=Representation+of+Natives+Act,+1936&source=gbs_navlinks_s|year=1999|publisher=Hart Publishing|isbn=978-0-313-29879-0|pages=197–202}}</ref> The Cape province had a qualified franchise which had allowed a small number of blacks in the Cape to vote for the common roll (although not to sit in parliament) in terms of the [[Cape Qualified Franchise]]. The qualified franchise dated back to the pre-Union period, when the Cape was a separate British colony; it also excluded poorer white men. The 1936 Act removed blacks to a separate roll – and halted the right to run for office; other earlier legislation removed the qualifications imposed in the Cape on whites.<ref>http://www.sahistory.org.za/dated-event/representation-natives-act-passed</ref>
With this act, the small black elite - most blacks never had the vote - were removed from the common rolls on which they had been able to register since 1854. Chiefs, local councils, urban advisory boards and election committees in all provinces were to elect four whites to the senate by a system of block voting. The act also created a Native Representative Council of six white officials, four nominated and twelve elected Africans.<ref>https://www.nelsonmandela.org/omalley/index.php/site/q/03lv01538/04lv01646/05lv01783.htm</ref>
==Repeal== This Act was repealed on 19 June 1959 by the [[Promotion of Bantu Self-government Act, 1959]].<ref>Promotion of Bantu Self-governing Act, Act No. 46 of 1959 http://www.aluka.org/stable/10.5555/al.sff.document.leg19590619.028.020.046</ref>
